\c 10
\ms1 The descendants of Noah and the tower of Babel
\s1 The descendants of Noah
\p
\v 1 After the flood Shem, Ham, and Japheth had many descendants.
\s1 The descendants of Japheth
\p
\v 2-5 Japheth's descendants had their own languages, tribes, and land. They were Gomer, Magog, Madai, Javan, Tubal, Meshech, and Tiras.
\p Gomer was the ancestor of Ashkenaz, Riphath, and Togarmah.
\p Javan was the ancestor of Elishah, Tarshish, Kittim, and Dodanim,\fe * \fq Dodanim: \ft Most Hebrew manuscripts; some Hebrew manuscripts and one ancient translation have “Rodanim”.\fe* who settled along the coast.
\s1 The descendants of Ham
\p
\v 6-20 Ham's descendants had their own languages, tribes, and land. They were Ethiopia,\f + \fr 10.6-20 \fq Ethiopia: \ft See the note at 2.13.\f* Egypt, Put, and Canaan.
\p Cush\f + \fr 10.6-20 \fq Cush: \ft See the note at 2.13.\f* was the ancestor of Seba, Havilah, Sabtah, Raamah, and Sabteca.
\p Raamah was the ancestor of Sheba and Dedan.
\p Cush was also the ancestor of Nimrod, a mighty warrior whose strength came from the \nd Lord\nd*. Nimrod is the reason for the saying, “You hunt like Nimrod with the strength of the \nd Lord\nd*!” Nimrod first ruled in Babylon, Erech, and Accad, all of\fe * \fq and Accad, all of: \ft Or “Accad, and Calneh”.\fe* which were in Babylonia.\fe * \fq Babylonia: \ft The Hebrew text has “Shinar”, another name for Babylonia.\fe* From there Nimrod went to Assyria and built the great city of Nineveh. He also built Rehoboth-Ir and Calah, as well as Resen, which is between Nineveh and Calah.
\p Egypt was the ancestor of Ludim, Anamim, Lehabim, Naphtuhim, Pathrusim, Casluhim, and Caphtorim, the ancestor of the Philistines.\fe * \fq Casluhim, and Caphtorim, the ancestor of the Philistines: \ft Hebrew “Caphtorim, and Casluhim, the ancestor of the Philistines”. The Philistines were from Caphtor (see Jeremiah 47.4; Amos 9.7), better known as Crete.\fe*
\p Canaan's sons were Sidon and Heth. He was also the ancestor of the Jebusites, the Amorites, the Girgashites, the Hivites, the Arkites, the Sinites, the Arvadites, the Zemarites, and the Hamathites.
\p Later the Canaanites spread from the territory of Sidon and went as far as Gaza in the direction of Gerar. They also went as far as Lasha in the direction of Sodom, Gomorrah, Admah, and Zeboiim.
\s1 The descendants of Shem
\p
\v 21-31 Shem's descendants had their own languages, tribes, and land. He was the elder brother of Japheth and the ancestor of the tribes of Eber.
\p Shem was the ancestor of Elam, Asshur, Arpachshad, Lud, and Aram.
\p Aram was the ancestor of Uz, Hul, Gether, and Mash.
\p Arpachshad was the father of Shelah and the grandfather of Eber, whose first son was named Peleg,\f + \fr 10.21-31 \fq Peleg: \ft In Hebrew “Peleg” means “divided”.\f* because it was during his time that tribes divided up the earth. Eber's second son was Joktan.
\p Joktan was the ancestor of Almodad, Sheleph, Hazarmaveth, Jerah, Hadoram, Uzal, Diklah, Obal, Abimael, Sheba, Ophir, Havilah, and Jobab. Their land reached from Mesha in the direction of Sephar, the hill country in the east.
\p
\v 32 This completes the list of Noah's descendants. After the flood their descendants became nations and spread all over the world.
